Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels — Over the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Fed has kept interest rates at zero levels and has also conducted multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, Bank of Japan, and the ECB have also followed the Fed's lead, each implementing their own version of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
Yet inflation has not been adequately boosted anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — — and economic performances — — are diverging.
Currently, the growth in the US and the UK is strong enough to allow them to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are intensifying QE, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
Why is there this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had current account deficits, making them debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtors rather than creditors, so the negative interest rate introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the US and the UK, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor countries around the world — — countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — — have also experienced negative interest rates, not only for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is far from beneficial.
Although low interest rates have had limited effects, the central banks of these economies still persist in this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring economic benefits, they will divert the conversation, refuting the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — — which appears flawless on the surface.
But in reality, this argument is full of holes.
Basic economics courses have mentioned this peculiar phenomenon called the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain environments, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
This is because a decline in interest rates reduces the income of savers, who will then cut back on spending, especially if they have savings goals for retirement.
All of this does not deny the general rule — — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
But the impact varies depending on the debt situation of the economy.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should benefit.
However, in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effects of interest rate floor monetary policy differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, because foreign asset positions were often small (as a percentage of GDP).
But now, foreign asset positions in major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly because of the leverage that caused the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage continues to increase at the national level.
Although current account imbalances have generally eased since the onset of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, diverging from deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them the main exception to the diversification of foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, global oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues have sharply declined — — many countries have lost half — — forcing them to generate deficits and rely on the massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending has become inevitable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem — — to some extent, it is a question of luxury — — is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall from falling import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But traditional debtor countries have such large current account surpluses that the debtor/country asymmetry continues to increase.
Most notably, since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeds the previous historical total.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may rise from 60% to 100% of GDP.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, struggling with low inflation despite the output gap slowly being filled and the US and Japan achieving full employment.
Central bank governors in debtor countries must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
ECB President Draghi recently acknowledged that the current monetary policy approach may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same is not the solution.
